## Example 3 — Coefficients Other Than 1

Expand:

`(2c - 6d)^4`

Use the Binomial Theorem:

`= 4C0(2c)^4 + 4C1(2c)^3(-6d) + 4C2(2c)^2(-6d)^2 + 4C3(2c)(-6d)^3 + 4C4(-6d)^4`

`= 16c^4 + 4(8c^3)(-6d) + 6(4c^2)(36d^2) + 4(2c)(-216d^3) + 1296d^4`

`= 16c^4 - 192c^3d + 864c^2d^2 - 1728cd^3 + 1296d^4`

### Study Tip

When the coefficients in the binomial are not `1`, the coefficients in the expansion are no longer symmetric, so the Binomial Theorem is often easier to use.

